#pbm("9.7")[
  Evaluate ${vb(r), vb(n) dot vb(L)}_(vb(q), vb(p))$ where $vb(r) = x vu(e)_x + y vu(e)_y + z vu(e)_z$ and $vb(n) = n_x vu(e)_x + n_y vu(e)_y + n_z vu(e)_z$ is a constant vector.

  *Angular momentum:* $vb(L) = vb(r) times vb(p)$, with components $L_k = sum_(i,j) epsilon_(i j k) x_i p_j$
]

#solution[
  *Express the Poisson bracket:*

  We want to calculate:
  $ {x_i, vb(n) dot vb(L)}_(vb(q), vb(p)) $

  for each component $x_i$ of $vb(r)$.

  *Expand $vb(n) dot vb(L)$:*

  $ vb(n) dot vb(L) = sum_j n_j L_j = sum_j n_j sum_(r, s) epsilon_(j r s) x_r p_s $

  *Calculate Poisson bracket:*

  $ {x_i, vb(n) dot vb(L)}_(vb(q), vb(p)) = {x_i, sum_j sum_(r, s) epsilon_(j r s) n_j x_r p_s}_(vb(q), vb(p)) $

  $ = sum_j sum_(r, s) epsilon_(j r s) n_j {x_i, x_r p_s}_(vb(q), vb(p)) $

  *Use Leibniz rule:*

  $ {x_i, x_r p_s}_(vb(q), vb(p)) = x_r {x_i, p_s}_(vb(q), vb(p)) + {x_i, x_r}_(vb(q), vb(p)) p_s $

  *Apply fundamental Poisson brackets:*

  $ cases(
    {x_i, p_s}_(vb(q), vb(p)) &= delta_(i s),
    {x_i, x_r}_(vb(q), vb(p)) &= 0
  ) $

  Therefore:
  $ {x_i, x_r p_s}_(vb(q), vb(p)) = x_r delta_(i s) $

  *Substitute back:*

  $ {x_i, vb(n) dot vb(L)}_(vb(q), vb(p)) &= sum_j sum_(r, s) epsilon_(j r s) n_j x_r delta_(i s) \
  &= sum_j sum_r epsilon_(j r i) n_j x_r $

  *Recognize as cross product:*

  The sum $sum_(j, r) epsilon_(j r i) n_j x_r$ is the $i$-th component of $vb(n) times vb(r)$.

  To see this, recall that the $i$-th component of $vb(n) times vb(r)$ is:
  $ (vb(n) times vb(r))_i = sum_(j, r) epsilon_(i j r) n_j x_r $

  We have $sum_(j, r) epsilon_(j r i) n_j x_r$. Using the property $epsilon_(j r i) = epsilon_(i j r)$ (cyclic permutation):
  $ sum_(j, r) epsilon_(j r i) n_j x_r = sum_(j, r) epsilon_(i j r) n_j x_r = (vb(n) times vb(r))_i $

  *Final answer:*

  #boxed[$ {vb(r), vb(n) dot vb(L)}_(vb(q), vb(p)) = vb(n) times vb(r) $]

  *Physical interpretation:*

  This result shows that the angular momentum $vb(L)$ generates infinitesimal rotations in phase space. Specifically, the Poisson bracket with $vb(n) dot vb(L)$ gives the infinitesimal rotation of the position vector about the axis $vb(n)$.

  More formally, if we consider the canonical transformation generated by $vb(n) dot vb(L)$:
  $ delta vb(r) = epsilon {vb(r), vb(n) dot vb(L)}_(vb(q), vb(p)) = epsilon (vb(n) times vb(r)) $

  This is precisely an infinitesimal rotation by angle $epsilon$ about the axis $vb(n)$, confirming that angular momentum is the generator of rotations in classical mechanics.
]

